website_summaries.verdict: Packed with nutrients, vitamins, and beet pulp to improve your cat's metabolism.
pros: Grain-free food is packed with natural ingredients like chicken, peas, potatoes, and beet pulp that contribute to a healthy metabolism
Free of wheat, grains, corn and soy
cons: Food sits at a higher price point than it's competitors

customer_reviews.title: Hit with the Cats
customer_reviews.text: Ordered this for the two shelter cats I've adopted -- and they love this! They were fed Purina Complete at the shelter. I've tried to convert them to a lot of other dried/moist foods that are supposedly more nutritionally sound than Purina Complete, including other Nutro offerings, with NO success, until now. This is the first dried food they actually seem to like -- and have continued to like a month in -- at least as much as their Purina Complete. Food arrived punctually. Food was ordered in 12/2018, and the expiration date of food received was 8/2019, which was around the same date as the food on the store shelves.
customer_reviews.author: Oh why not?

customer_reviews.title: Great product!  Timmy went Wild over Wild! (Wild Frontier)
customer_reviews.text: I use raw and wet foods mostly, along with "greens" but wanted a high quality dry. I did some research and decided to give this brand a try. Super Product. Salmon arrived early, waiting for the chicken blend. (background in nutrition, holistic therapies)
customer_reviews.author: Fish Saver

customer_reviews.title: Stinky food, stinky poops!
customer_reviews.text: We switched to this food after our 10 year old began to be sick from her long-time brand. She tolerated it fine. She LOVED the food, BUT it was way to smelly to have in the house, and her litter box reeked, eventually smelling up the whole room despite our daily cleaning. The other problem was that the kibbles were too big, so she would crunch them into pieces, sending the pieces flying from her food maze, and then would never touch the broken pieces again, so there was a lot of mess and waste. Her coat got rough too. I am skeptical of "grain-free" food that contains other vegetable ingredients that a cat would never eat in the wild.
customer_reviews.author: Amie

customer_reviews.title: My cat likes Wild Frontier better than EVO or Science Diet Sensitive Skin.  EVO has closed up.
customer_reviews.text: I bought this cat food at the recommendation of EVO, which has been discontinued. I switched to EVO about a year ago to reduce the carbohydrates my cat was eating. (He was on Science Diet Sensitive Stomach and Skin - Brewers Rice is first ingredient; 31% protein). EVO had 50% protein, first ingredient was herring. The closing EVO web page recommended Wild Frontier by Nutro. My cat prefers this to both the remaining EVO and the Science Diet. Wild Frontier has 40% protein, and first ingredient is Salmon. I consider this a winner.
customer_reviews.author: Ernie

customer_reviews.title: Not for my cats
customer_reviews.text: My friend recommended this cat food to me so that I may try it with my cats as her cats love it. Well my, after every time I give them this cat food, throw up so unfortunately it does not agree with my cats, so after a few failed attempts and figuring out that this was making me cats sick, I stopped giving it to them. But that’s that thing about cat food, it’s a trial-and-error situation. One cat might love it while another cat will hate it. On a side note, the dog likes it and eats it up and it agrees with his digestion.
customer_reviews.author: E. Khaletski

customer_reviews.title: Good quality
customer_reviews.text: My cat used to throw up frequently. I worried about what I fed her but wasn't sure what to do about it. I was lucky to receive this food for review, then immediately bought an 11 lbs. bag when I realized she was no longer throwing up. This is our second 11 lbs. bag. I really like that the primary ingredients are natural items similar to what a cat would eat in the wild. No, it's not perfect, but it is about as close as you can get from a dry, mass-market food.
customer_reviews.author: JDW

customer_reviews.title: Picky cats inhaled it!

I found this after reading reviews on a cat food site and even though it's expensive I was running out of ideas! Especially since they have to have grain free... They are WOLFING this down. I flew through the smallest bag in slightly over a week. Ordered a bigger one, hopefully it ships fast!

The other two cats will nibble on occasion, but apparently the food is high-cal, which one of our cats does not need. You might check that out before buying.

customer_reviews.title: Our newly adopted cats love this food.
customer_reviews.text: The Humane Society was feeding all the cats this brand and flavor so we continued on feeding our new fur babies when we brought them home. They love it and I feel it keeps them slim and shiny as well. They are both 1 year old and indoor cats so I feed them in 2 bowls 1/3 cup 3 times a day each bowl and that works out very well for them. I like the idea of feeding them throughout the day so the food doesn't get stale over time and I also noticed that they seem to like coming over to the bowls 3 times a day- they are smarties and know what time breakfast lunch and dinner is.

customer_reviews.title: Helped my Bombay

By the time she finished the second bag her fur had turned black again. Entire coat has improved. Cats can be picky about their food but she readily adapted to this change.

customer_reviews.title: They love it!

I’ve owned cats and dogs for 25 years and an animal’s coat and stools are a good indicator of the quality of the food. Will be sticking with this one!
